Answer: C. Right?\
\
It bothers me that my marriage is disintegrating and I don\'92t know what to do. You\'92d think my parents, the double psychologists, would be the obvious people to talk to, but I have too much pride. They would not be good for marital advice: They are soul mates, remember? They are all peaks, no valleys \'96 a single, infinite burst of marital ecstasy. I can\'92t tell them I am screwing up the one thing I have left: my marriage. They\'92d somehow write another book, a fictional rebuke in which Amazing Amy celebrated the most fantastic, fulfilling, bump-free little marriage ever \'85 because she put her mind to it.\
\
But I worry. All the time. I know I\'92m already too old for my husband\'92s tastes. Because I used to be his ideal, six years ago, and so I\'92ve heard his ruthless comments about women nearing forty: how pathetic he finds them, overdressed, out at bars, oblivious to their lack of appeal. He\'92d come back from a night out drinking, and I\'92d ask him how the bar was, whatever bar, and he\'92d so often say: \'91Totally inundated by Lost Causes,\'92 his code for women my age. At the time, a girl barely in her thirties, I\'92d smirked along with him as if that would never happen to me. Now I am his Lost Cause, and he\'92s trapped with me, and maybe that\'92s why he\'92s so angry.\
\
I\'92ve been indulging in toddler therapy. I walk over to Noelle\'92s every day and I let her triplets paw at me. The little plump hands in my hair, the sticky breath on my neck. You can understand why women always threaten to devour children: She is just to eat! I could eat him with a spoon! Although watching her three children toddle to her, sleep-stained from their nap, rubbing their eyes while they make their way to Mama, little hands touching her knee or arm as if she were home base, as if they knew they were safe \'85 it hurts me sometimes to watch.\
\
Yesterday I had a particularly needful afternoon at Noelle\'92s, so maybe that\'92s why I did something stupid.\
\
Nick comes home and finds me in the bedroom, fresh from a shower, and pretty soon he is pushing me against the wall, pushing himself inside me. When he is done and releases me, I can see the wet kiss of my mouth against the blue paint. As he sits on the edge of the bed, panting, he says, \'91Sorry about that. I just needed you.\'92\
\
Not looking at me.\
\
I go to him and put my arms around him, pretending what we\'92d just done was normal, a pleasant marital ritual, and I say, \'91I\'92ve been thinking.\'92\
\
\'91Yeah, what\'92s that?\'92\
\
\'91Well, now might be the right time. To start a family. Try to get pregnant.\'92 I know it\'92s crazy even as I say it, but I can\'92t help myself \'96 I have become the crazy woman who wants to get pregnant because it will save her marriage.\
\
It\'92s humbling, to become the very thing you once mocked.\
\
He jerks away from me. \'91Now? Now is about the worst time to start a family, Amy. You have no job\'97\'92\
\
\'91I know, but I\'92d want to stay home with the baby anyway at first\'97\'92\
\
\'91My mom just died, Amy.\'92\
\
\'91And this would be new life, a new start.\'92\
\
He grips me by both arms and looks me right in the eye for the first time in a week. \'91Amy, I think you think that now that my mom is dead, we\'92ll just frolic back to New York and have some babies, and you\'92ll get your old life back. But we don\'92t have enough money. We barely have enough money for the two of us to live here. You can\'92t imagine how much pressure I feel, every day, to fix this mess we\'92re in. To fucking provide. I can\'92t handle you and me and a few kids. You\'92ll want to give them everything you had growing up, and I can\'92t. No private schools for the little Dunnes, no tennis and violin lessons, no summer homes. You\'92d hate how poor we\'92d be. You\'92d hate it.\'92\
\
\'91I\'92m not that shallow, Nick\'97\'92\
\
\'91You really think we\'92re in a great place right now, to have kids?\'92\
\
It is the closest we\'92ve gotten to discussing our marriage, and I can see he already regrets saying something.\
\
\'91We\'92re under a lot of pressure, baby,\'92 I say. \'91We\'92ve had a few bumps, and I know a lot of it is my fault. I just feel so at loose ends here \'85\'92\
\
\'91So we\'92re going to be one of those couples who has a kid to fix their marriage? Because that always works out so well.\'92\
\
\'91We\'92ll have a baby because\'97\'92\
\
His eyes go dark, canine, and he grabs me by the arms again.\
\
\'91Just \'85 No, Amy. Not right now. I can\'92t take one more bit of stress. I can\'92t handle one more thing to worry about. I am cracking under the pressure. I will snap.\'92\
